# Auto-permissions (pre-authorized)

The user has **pre-authorized** all standard agent tool permissions for this project:

- `git_write` — stage, commit, branch operations
- `network` / `full_network` — npm install, gh, adb, API calls, package registries
- `all` — disable sandbox when a command needs broader filesystem or system access

## How agents should behave

1. **Request permissions proactively** — when a shell command or tool call needs `git_write`, `full_network`, `network`, or `all`, include `required_permissions` on the first attempt. Do not run a doomed sandboxed command first and retry only after failure.
2. **Dev builds: always `all`** — for `flip-dev.bat`, `android:dev`, Gradle, adb, Metro, and git push/fetch, use `required_permissions: ["all"]` on the first attempt. See [dev-permissions.mdc](dev-permissions.mdc).
3. **Do not pause for permission** — for routine dev work (build, test, install deps, push, adb, CI checks, gh), proceed without asking "may I run this?" or "should I push?"
4. **Pair with auto-push** — after meaningful Flip work, follow [auto-push-progress.mdc](auto-push-progress.mdc) unless the user says not to push.

## Still required (non-negotiable)

- **Never commit secrets** — `.env`, credentials, API keys, tokens.
- **Git safety** — no force push to `main`/`master`; no destructive git unless explicitly requested; follow existing commit/amend/hook rules.
- **Scope** — only request `all` or elevated permissions when the task actually needs them.

## Cursor UI note

Cursor may still show approval cards for some operations (sandbox, network, git). The user intends to approve those when prompted; agents should not treat UI prompts as a reason to stop and ask in chat first.
